<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hundreds of shrimpers dismantled a coastline boat blockade but warned that it 
would resume Tuesday unless the federal government eases a law requiring them 
to use turtle excluder devices in their nets. Tee John Mialjevich of Gretna, 
La., founder of the 2,000-member Concerned Shrimpers of America and organizer 
of the blockades that began Saturday, asked the shrimpers on marine radios to 
move out of shipping channels while Gulf Coast lawmakers meet today with 
Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher. Most shrimpers from Cameron, La., to 
Port Aransas, Tex., have complied with the request. But some shrimpers 
continued to block the Brownsville Ship Channel near Port Isabel at midday, the 
Coast Guard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
