<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two former government officials announced that they will seek to qualify an 
initiative for the 1990 ballot that would limit to eight years the time anyone 
could serve in the Legislature. Jerry Partain, a former director of the state 
Department of Forestry, and John E. McDonald, a former assistant legislative 
counsel, said they are sponsoring the measure to remove career politicians from 
office and encourage the election of "citizen legislators." If successful, the 
measure sponsored by the two Republicans could substantially reduce the 
influence of the Democratic Party in the Legislature, because the Assembly and 
Senate are now controlled by Democrats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
