<TEXT>
<P>
The breakaway state of Northern Cyprus has jailed 91 Greek Cypriots for their 
part in a protest that has soured Greco-Turkish ties before talks on reunifying 
the Mediterranean island. The protesters, most of them women, were seized last 
week after breaking through the U.N. buffer zone lines in a "walk home" action 
last week to mark the 15th anniversary of Turkey's invasion of Cyprus. Of the 
108 arrested, 91 were fined and sentenced to three days in jail by the Nicosia 
district court. Sixteen women were freed on bail and one girl, aged 14, was 
freed unconditionally. Ten refused to comply with bail and were also jailed. 
About 100 Greek-Cypriots broke into the U.N. buffer zone west of Nicosia during 
another "walk home" over the weekend but were stopped before reaching Turkish 
lines. 
