<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHRYSLER MAY BE SET TO CUT WHITE-COLLAR WORK FORCE BY 10% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Industry analysts said today that Chrysler Corp. will soon announce a program 
under which it will substantially reduce its number of white-collar workers to 
raise profitability levels. 
</P>
<P>
Sources said the cuts could affect as much as 10% of Chrysler's salaried work 
force, which is now about 31,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
Although Chrysler declined to comment on the specifics of such a program, 
company spokeswoman Karen Stewart hinted that an announcement could be made by 
company Chairman Lee Iacocca on Thursday at a weekly meeting of top company 
managers. 
</P>
<P>
"Ongoing belt-tightening is simply a way of life at Chrysler as we look for 
ways to reduce cost," Stewart said, calling any job reductions a "basic 
competitive action" necessary because of incentive costs and increased industry 
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
